{"title_page": "Brodsky", "text_new": "'''Brodsky''', feminine: '''Brodskaya''' ([[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]: \u0411\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439, [[Russian language|Russian]]: \u0411\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439)  is a [[toponymic surname]] derived from [[Brody]], a town in [[Ukraine]].  The name is common among [[Ashkenazi]] Jews.\nCzech-language forms are '''Brodsk\u00fd''' and '''Brodsk\u00e1'''.\n\nNotable people with this surname include:\n* [[Nina Brodskaya]], Soviet singer\n* [[Yulia Brodskaya]], artist and illustrator\n* [[Adam Brodsky]], American Drummer / Musician\n* [[Adolph Brodsky]] (1851\u20131929), Russian violinist and music teacher\n* [[Alexander Brodsky]], contemporary architect and artist\n* [[Chuck Brodsky]] (born 1960), American musician\n* [[Gail Brodsky]] (born 1991), American tennis player\n* [[Isaac Brodsky]] (1884\u20131939), Soviet painter\n* [[Jascha Brodsky]] (1907\u20131997), Ukrainian-American violinist\n* [[Joel Brodsky]] (1939\u20132007), photographer\n* [[Joseph Brodsky]] (1940\u20131996), Russian poet and Nobel Prize winner\n* [[Joseph Brodsky (lawyer)]], chief lawyer for the [[International Labor Defense]]\n* [[Julian A. Brodsky]] (born 1933), American businessman\n* [[Lazar Brodsky]] (1848\u20131904), Ukrainian businessman and philanthropist\n* [[Louis Daniel Brodsky]] (born 1941), American poet\n* [[Michael Brodsky]] (born 1948), American novelist and playwright\n* [[Mykhaylo Brodskyy]], (born 1959), Ukrainian politician and businessman\n* [[Richard Brodsky]] (1946-2020), American politician and lawyer\n* [[Sol Brodsky]] (1923\u20131984), American comic book artist and head of production of Marvel Comics\n* [[Stephen Brodsky]], lead singer and guitar player for [[alternative metal]] band [[Cave In]]\n* [[Vadim Brodsky]] (born 1950), Ukrainian-Polish violinist\n* [[Vsevolod Brodsky]] (1909\u20131981), Russian-Soviet painter and illustrator, Editor-in-Chief of Molodaya Gvardiya (Young Guard) publishing house\n* [[Vlastimil Brodsk\u00fd]] (1920\u20132002), Czech actor\n* [[Tereza Brodsk\u00e1]] (born 1968), Czech actress\n* {{ill|Marek Brodsk\u00fd|cs}}, Czech actor, singer, and songwriter\n\n===Fictional Characters===\n* Jacob Broadsky, a villain in the television show ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]''\n* Walker Brodsky, a young artist and love interest from [[Disney Channel]] series ''[[Andi Mack]]''\n\n==See also==\n* [[Brodsky Quartet]]\n* [[Brodzki]]\n\n{{surname}}\n\n[[Category:Ukrainian-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Czech-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Russian-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Toponymic surnames]]\n", "text_old": "'''Brodsky''', feminine: '''Brodskaya''' ([[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]: \u0411\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439, [[Russian language|Russian]]: \u0411\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439)  is a [[toponymic surname]] derived from [[Brody]], a town in [[Ukraine]].  The name is common among [[Ashkenazi]] Jews.\nCzech-language forms are '''Brodsk\u00fd''' and '''Brodsk\u00e1'''.\n\nNotable people with this surname include:\n* [[Nina Brodskaya]], Soviet singer\n* [[Yulia Brodskaya]], artist and illustrator\n* [[Adam Brodsky]], American Drummer / Musician\n* [[Adolph Brodsky]] (1851\u20131929), Russian violinist and music teacher\n* [[Alexander Brodsky]], contemporary architect and artist\n* [[Chuck Brodsky]] (born 1960), American musician\n* [[Gail Brodsky]] (born 1991), American tennis player\n* [[Isaac Brodsky]] (1884\u20131939), Soviet painter\n* [[Jascha Brodsky]] (1907\u20131997), Ukrainian-American violinist\n* [[Joel Brodsky]] (1939\u20132007), photographer\n* [[Joseph Brodsky]] (1940\u20131996), Russian poet and Nobel Prize winner\n* [[Joseph Brodsky (lawyer)]], chief lawyer for the [[International Labor Defense]]\n* [[Julian A. Brodsky]] (born 1933), American businessman\n* [[Lazar Brodsky]] (1848\u20131904), Ukrainian businessman and philanthropist\n* [[Louis Daniel Brodsky]] (born 1941), American poet\n* [[Michael Brodsky]] (born 1948), American novelist and playwright\n* [[Mykhaylo Brodskyy]], (born 1959), Ukrainian politician and businessman\n* [[Richard Brodsky]] (1946-2010), American politician and lawyer\n* [[Sol Brodsky]] (1923\u20131984), American comic book artist and head of production of Marvel Comics\n* [[Stephen Brodsky]], lead singer and guitar player for [[alternative metal]] band [[Cave In]]\n* [[Vadim Brodsky]] (born 1950), Ukrainian-Polish violinist\n* [[Vsevolod Brodsky]] (1909\u20131981), Russian-Soviet painter and illustrator, Editor-in-Chief of Molodaya Gvardiya (Young Guard) publishing house\n* [[Vlastimil Brodsk\u00fd]] (1920\u20132002), Czech actor\n* [[Tereza Brodsk\u00e1]] (born 1968), Czech actress\n* {{ill|Marek Brodsk\u00fd|cs}}, Czech actor, singer, and songwriter\n\n===Fictional Characters===\n* Jacob Broadsky, a villain in the television show ''[[Bones (TV series)|Bones]]''\n* Walker Brodsky, a young artist and love interest from [[Disney Channel]] series ''[[Andi Mack]]''\n\n==See also==\n* [[Brodsky Quartet]]\n* [[Brodzki]]\n\n{{surname}}\n\n[[Category:Ukrainian-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Czech-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Russian-language surnames]]\n[[Category:Toponymic surnames]]\n", "name_user": "DavidSteirman", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brodsky"}
{"title_page": "Taylor Penny", "text_new": "[[File:Whitcombe, Battle of the Saints.jpg|thumb|330px|The Battle of the Saintes]]\nCaptain '''Taylor Penny''' (1721&ndash;1786) was an 18th-century officer of the [[Royal Navy]] who came to fame at the [[Battle of the Saintes]].\n\n==Life==\n\nHe was born in [[Weymouth, Dorset|Weymouth]] in [[Dorset]] in 1721, probably into a seafaring family.\n\nHe was commissioned as a lieutenant in the [[Royal Navy]] on 6 August 1745. In 1755 he joined the newly converted [[HMS Firebrand (1755)|HMS Firebrand]] and on 31 December of that year was promoted to commander.<ref>https://morethannelson.com/officer/taylor-penny/</ref>\n\nIn November 1757 he transferred to be captain of the newly completed [[HMS Aldborough (1756)|HMS Aldborough]]. He was mainly employed on convoy duty. In 1760 he transferred to the newly completed 44-gun [[HMS Looe (1759)|HMS Looe]]. On this ship he captured the [[French ship Jupiter|Jupiter]] in June 1762. Soon after he captured a small Spanish privateer, Maria, and the 4-gun Joseph, which he took to [[Cork (city)|Cork]] in [[Ireland]]. Both these actions were during the [[Seven Years' War]].\n\nFrom 1762 to 1777 he had no active commissions (and possibly had a family life in Dorset during this period).\n\nIn June 1778 he was appointed commander of the 70-gun [[HMS Burford (1757)|HMS Burford]], one of the largest ships in the [[Royal Navy]] at the time. He was replaced by Captain [[Peter Rainier]] in October of that year. He was then given a more permanent positioon as captain and commander of [[HMS Marlborough (1767)|HMS Marlborough]] in June 1779. On this ship he took part in the [[Channel Fleet]] retreat and the [[Moonlight Battle]] off [[Cape St. Vincent]] on 16 January 1780. Under Admiral [[Robert Digby (Royal Navy officer)|Robert Digby]] in February 1780 he captured the French ship [[French ship Prot\u00e9e (1772)|Protee]] which was then recommissioned in the Royal Navy as HMS Prothee.<ref>British Warships in the Age of Sail 1714-1792 R Winfield</ref>\n\nIn the campaign of June to December 1780, still under Admiral Digby, alongside Captain Richard Onslow on [[HMS Bellona (1760)|HMS Bellona]] they captured the 54-gun Dutch ship Princess Carolina (on 30 December).\n\nOn 12 April 1781 he aided the relief of [[Gibraltar]]. Later in 1781 he sailed to the [[Leeward Islands]] to join Admiral [[George Rodney]]'s fleet patrolling the [[West Indies]].\n\nOn 12 April 1782 he headed the attack on the French fleet as part of the [[Battle of the Saintes]]. She approached to stand 150m from the French line.\n<ref>Famous Fighters of the Fleet, Edward Fraser, 1904, p.105</ref> Following this action he attached to [[Hugh Pigot (Royal Navy admiral)|Admiral Hugh Pigot]]'s fleet which went to North America, patrolling the seas off [[Boston]].\n\nBoth Penny and the Marlborough were paid off by the Royal Navy in July 1783.\n\nPenny then returned to his home town of Weymouth where he served as mayor 1785/6.\n\nHe died on 18 April 1786 in [[Wyke Regis]] aged 64 and was buried in All Saints churchyard there on 19 April 1782.<ref>http://memorials.rmg.co.uk/author/dedwards/page/307/</ref>\n\n==Family==\n\nPenny was married and his wife outlived him.\n\nThey did not have children. However he took a young Weymouth man, [[Joseph Spear]], his aid in receiving a commission into the navy in 1779. Spear had \na very illustrious career.<ref>The Gentleman's Magazine vol.162, July 1837</ref>\n\nHis great nephew Major General Nicholas Penny was killed in action at [[Kukerowlee]] in April 1858 during the [[Indian mutiny]].<ref>http://glosters.tripod.com/IM6.htm</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Penny, Taylor}}\n[[Category:1721 births]]\n[[Category:1786 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Dorset]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Whitcombe, Battle of the Saints.jpg|thumb|330px|The Battle of the Saintes]]\nCaptain '''Taylor Penny''' (1721&ndash;1786) was an 18th-century officer of the [[Royal Navy]] who came to fame at the [[Battle of the Saintes]].\n\n==Life==\n\nHe was born in [[Weymouth, Dorset|Weymouth]] in [[Dorset]] in 1721, probably into a seafaring family.\n\nHe was commissioned as a lieutenant in the [[Royal Navy]] on 6 August 1745. In 1755 he joined the newly converted [[HMS Firebrand (1755)|HMS Firebrand]] and on 31 December of that year was promoted to commander.<ref>https://morethannelson.com/officer/taylor-penny/</ref>\n\nIn November 1757 he transferred to be captain of the newly completed [[HMS Aldborough (1756)|HMS Aldborough]]. He was mainly employed on convoy duty. In 1760 he transferred to the newly completed 44-gun [[HMS Looe (1759)|HMS Looe]]. On this ship he captured the [[French ship Jupiter|Jupiter]] in June 1762. Soon after he captured a small Spanish privateer, Maria, and the 4-gun Joseph, which he took to [[Cork, Ireland|Cork]] in [[Ireland]]. Both these actions were during the [[Seven Years' War]].\n\nFrom 1762 to 1777 he had no active commissions (and possibly had a family life in Dorset during this period).\n\nIn June 1778 he was appointed commander of the 70-gun [[HMS Burford (1757)|HMS Burford]], one of the largest ships in the [[Royal Navy]] at the time. He was replaced by Captain [[Peter Rainier]] in October of that year. He was then given a more permanent positioon as captain and commander of [[HMS Marlborough (1767)|HMS Marlborough]] in June 1779. On this ship he took part in the [[Channel Fleet]] retreat and the [[Moonlight Battle]] off [[Cape St. Vincent]] on 16 January 1780. Under Admiral [[Robert Digby (Royal Navy officer)|Robert Digby]] in February 1780 he captured the French ship [[French ship Prot\u00e9e (1772)|Protee]] which was then recommissioned in the Royal Navy as HMS Prothee.<ref>British Warships in the Age of Sail 1714-1792 R Winfield</ref>\n\nIn the campaign of June to December 1780, still under Admiral Digby, alongside Captain Richard Onslow on [[HMS Bellona (1760)|HMS Bellona]] they captured the 54-gun Dutch ship Princess Carolina (on 30 December).\n\nOn 12 April 1781 he aided the relief of [[Gibraltar]]. Later in 1781 he sailed to the [[Leeward Islands]] to join Admiral [[George Rodney]]'s fleet patrolling the [[West Indies]].\n\nOn 12 April 1782 he headed the attack on the French fleet as part of the [[Battle of the Saintes]]. She approached to stand 150m from the French line.\n<ref>Famous Fighters of the Fleet, Edward Fraser, 1904, p.105</ref> Following this action he attached to [[Hugh Pigot (Royal Navy admiral)|Admiral Hugh Pigot]]'s fleet which went to North America, patrolling the seas off [[Boston]].\n\nBoth Penny and the Marlborough were paid off by the Royal Navy in July 1783.\n\nPenny then returned to his home town of Weymouth where he served as mayor 1785/6.\n\nHe died on 18 April 1786 in [[Wyke Regis]] aged 64 and was buried in All Saints churchyard there on 19 April 1782.<ref>http://memorials.rmg.co.uk/author/dedwards/page/307/</ref>\n\n==Family==\n\nPenny was married and his wife outlived him.\n\nThey did not have children. However he took a young Weymouth man, [[Joseph Spear]], his aid in receiving a commission into the navy in 1779. Spear had \na very illustrious career.<ref>The Gentleman's Magazine vol.162, July 1837</ref>\n\nHis great nephew Major General Nicholas Penny was killed in action at [[Kukerowlee]] in April 1858 during the [[Indian mutiny]].<ref>http://glosters.tripod.com/IM6.htm</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Penny, Taylor}}\n[[Category:1721 births]]\n[[Category:1786 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Dorset]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toCork(link changed toCork (city)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taylor_Penny"}
