alifornia\n| province          = \n| country           = US\n| coordinates       = \n| latitude          = \n| longitude         = \n| district          = \n| oversight         = \n| accreditation     = \n| campus            = \n| colors            = \n| colours           = \n| athletics         = \n| houses            = \n| student_union     = \n| nickname          = \n| mascot            = \n| free_label        = [[Emblem]]\n| free_text         = \n| rival             = \n| yearbook          = \n| newpaper          = \n| free_label_1      = Campus size\n| free_1            = {{convert|12|acre|m2}}\n| free_label_2      = \n| free_2            = \n| free_label_3      = \n| free_3            = \n| test_name         = \n| test_average      = \n| national_ranking  = \n| website           = \n| footnotes         = \n| picture           = [[File:HWMS.jpg|200px]]\n| picture_caption   = The former Administration Building, Middle School (demolished summer 2008)\n| picture2          = \n| picture_caption2  = \n}}\n{{Infobox school\n| name              = Upper School\n| native_name       = \n| image             = \n| image_size        = \n| alt               = \n| caption           = \n| logo              = \n| motto             = \n| established       = \n| closed            = \n| type              = \n| status            = \n| category_label    = \n| category          = \n| gender_label      = \n| gender            = \n| affiliation       = \n| affiliations      = \n| administrator     = \n| assst_admin       = \n| president         = \n| chairman_label    = \n| chairman          = \n| rector            = \n| principal         = \n| asst principal    = \n| campus_director   = \n| headmaster        = \n| head_name         = Second Master\n| head              = \n| head_name2        = Assistant Headmaster\n| head2             = \n| dean              = \n| founder           = \n| chaplain          = \n| officer_in_charge = \n| faculty           = \n| teaching_staff    = \n| enrollment        = 871 (2015\u201316)<ref name=\"nces_psch\" />\n| enrollment_as_of  = \n| grades            = [[tenth grade|10]]\u2013[[twelfth grade|12]]\n| streetaddress     = 3700 Coldwater Canyon Avenue\n| city              = [[Studio City]]\n| state             = California\n| province          = \n| country           = United States\n| coordinates       = \n| latitude          = \n| longitude         = \n| district          = \n| oversight         = \n| accreditation     = \n| campus            = \n| colors            = \n| colours           = \n| athletics         = \n| houses            = \n| student_union     = \n| nickname          = \n| mascot            = \n| free_label        = [[Emblem]]\n| free_text         = \n| rival             = \n| yearbook          = \n| newpaper          = \n| free_label_1      = Campus size\n| free_1            = {{convert|22|acre|m2}}\n| picture           = [[File:Ted Slavin Field.jpg|200px]]\n| picture_caption   = Ted Slavin Field, Upper School\n| picture2          = \n| picture_caption2  = Ted Slavin Field, Upper School\n}}\n'''Harvard-Westlake School''' is an independent, [[co-educational]] [[university preparatory school|university preparatory]] day school consisting of two campuses located in [[Los Angeles, California|Los Angeles]], [[California]], with approximately 1,600 students enrolled in grades seven through 12. Its two predecessor organizations began as for-profit schools before turning non-profit, and eventually merging. It is not affiliated with [[Harvard University]] despite being named after it.\n\nThe school has two campuses, the middle school campus in [[Holmby Hills]] and the high school, or what Harvard-Westlake refers to as their Upper School, in [[Studio City, Los Angeles, California|Studio City]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hw.com/about/Our-Campuses | title = Our Campuses | accessdate = May 5, 2018}}</ref> It is a member of the [[G30 Schools]] group.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx | title = Move over G8\u2014this is G20 > Harvard Westlake Chronicle | accessdate = May 19, 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071028073515/http://students.hw.com/chronicle/tabid/1274/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/230/Move-over-G8this-is-G20.aspx |archive-date=October 28, 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n=== Harvard School for Boys ===\nThe Harvard School for Boys was established in 1900 by [[Grenville C. Emery]] as a [[military academy]], on the site of a [[barley]] field located at the corner of Western Avenue and Sixteenth Street (now [[Venice Boulevard]]) in Los Angeles, California.<ref>{{cite book | url = https://books.google.com/?id=YihCiW11oLoC&pg=PA67&dq=harvard+westlake+emery#v=onepage&q=harvard+westlake+emery&f=false | title = West Adams | first1 = Suzanne Tarbell | last1 = Cooper | first2 = Don | last2 = Lynch | first3 = John G. | last3 = Kurtz | date = August 19, 2018 | publisher = Arcadia Publishing | via = Google Books | isbn = 9780738559209}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web | url = https://www.dailynews.com/2013/04/29/harvard-westlake-creates-employee-friendly-environment/ | title = Harvard Westlake creates employee friendly environment | date = April 29, 2013 | publisher =}}</ref> Emery was originally from Boston, and around 1900 he wrote to Harvard University to ask permission to use the Harvard name for his new secondary school, and received permission from the university's then-President, [[Charles W. Eliot]].<ref>{{cite book | url = https://books.google.com/?id=LhMGSDiQghEC&pg=PA222&dq=harvard+westlake#v=onepage&q=harvard+westlake&f=false | title = Damn Right!: Behind the Scenes with Berkshire Hathaway Billionaire Charlie Munger | first = Janet | last = Lowe | date = October 30, 2000 | publisher = John Wiley & Sons | via = Google Books | isbn = 9780471244738}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated1 /> In 1911, it secured endorsement from the [[Episcopal Church in the United States of America|Episcopal Church]], becoming a [[non-profit organization]]. In 1937, the school moved to its present-day campus at the former Hollywood Country Club on Coldwater Canyon in Studio City after receiving a $25,000 (${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|25000|1937|r=-3}}}} in current dollar terms) loan from aviation pioneer [[Donald Wills Douglas, Sr.|Donald Douglas]].<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref name=autogenerated1 /> In the late 1960s and early 1970s, the Harvard School gradually discontinued both boarding and its standing as a military academy, while expanding its enrollment, courses, classes, teachers, and curriculum.<ref name=\"history\">{{cite web | url = http://www.hw.com/introduction/history.html | title = Harvard Westlake History | accessdate = May 19, 2007 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070426160507/http://www.hw.com/introduction/history.html | archivedate = April 26, 2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Westlake School for Girls ===\nThe Westlake School for Girls was established in 1904 by Jessica Smith Vance and Frederica de Laguna in what is now [[downtown Los Angeles]], California, as an exclusively female institution offering both elementary and secondary education. It was so-named because it was near Westlake Park, now known as [[MacArthur Park]].<ref name=autogenerated1 /> At the time, the school was a for-profit alternative to the already-established [[Marlborough School (Los Angeles)|Marlborough School]], which had been established as a non-profit before the turn of the century.\n\nIt moved to its present-day campus located on North Faring Road in [[Holmby Hills]], California, in 1927.<ref name=autogenerated1 /> The school was purchased by Sydney Temple, whose daughter, Helen Temple Dickinson, was headmistress until 1966, when Westlake became a non-profit institution.  The Temple family owned the school until 1977, with Dickinson serving in an [[ex officio]] capacity.  In 1968 Westlake became exclusively a secondary school.<ref name=\"history\"/>\n\n=== Merger ===\nAs both schools continued to grow in size towards the late 1980s, and as gender exclusivity became less of a factor both in the schools' reputations and desirability, the trustees of both Harvard and Westlake effectuated a merger in 1989. The two institutions had long been ''de facto'' sister schools, and interacted socially. Complete integration and coeducation began in 1991.<ref name=\"history\"/>\n\n=== Cheating scandal ===\nIn 2008, six sophomores were expelled and more than a dozen other students faced suspensions as a result of a cheating scandal.<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Rivera | first1 = Carla | title = Scandal rocks private school | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2008/feb/27/local/me-harvard27 | accessdate = March 29, 2017 | publisher = Los Angeles Times | date = February 27, 2008}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1 = William-Ross | first1 = Linsday | title = Harvard-Westlake Students Expelled for Cheating | url = http://laist.com/2008/02/27/harvardwestlake.php | publisher = LAist | accessdate = March 29, 2017 | date = February 27, 2008|url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20150822205556/http://laist.com/2008/02/27/harvardwestlake.php | archivedate = August 22, 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Campuses ==\nCurrently, the school is split between the two campuses, with grades 7\u20139, the Middle School, located at the former Westlake campus in [[Holmby Hills]] and grades 10\u201312, the Upper School, located at the former Harvard campus in [[Studio City, Los Angeles, California|Studio City]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hw.com/ | title = Harvard-Westlake School | accessdate = May 19, 2007}}</ref>\n\nThe Middle School completed a four-year modernization in September 2008, replacing the original administration building,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hw.com/msmp | title = Harvard-Westlake School Middle School Modernization Project > MSMP Home | accessdate = May 19, 2007 |url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080518053944/http://www.hw.com/msmp/ | archivedate = May 18, 2008}}</ref> the library, and the instrumental music building.  The campus now features a new library, two levels of classrooms in the Academic Center, the new Seaver Science Center, a turf field, a new administration office, a putting green, a long jump pit, and a large parking lot.  Another significant addition of the project was the Bing Performing Arts Center which features a two-level, 800-seat theater, a suite of practice rooms, a few large classrooms for band, orchestra, and choir classes, a black box theater, a dance studio, and a room with atomic pianos for composing electronic music.{{fact|date=March 2018}} \n\nRemnants of the former Middle School campus include the Marshall Center, which houses a gymnasium, weight room, and wrestling room, a {{convert|25|yd|m|adj=on}} swimming pool and diving boards, an outdoor basketball court, and a tennis court.  Reynolds Hall, an academic building which is home to history, foreign language, and visual arts classes, began a modernization effort in June 2014 to be completed by September 2015.  The building was named Wang Hall in honor of two parents who donated approximately $5,000,000 to fund the project.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://hwchronicle.com/school-holds-wang-hall-reception/ | title = School holds Wang Hall reception - The Harvard-Westlake Chronicle | website = hwchronicle.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://hwchronicle.com/administration-trustees-rename-reynolds-hall/ | title = Administration, trustees rename Reynolds Hall - The Harvard-Westlake Chronicle | website = hwchronicle.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Upper School features the Munger Science Center and computer lab; the Rugby building which houses the English department, 300-seat theater, costume shop, and drama lab; the Seaver building, home to the foreign language and history departments as well as administrative offices and the visitor lobby; Chalmers, which houses the performing arts and math departments, book store, cafeteria, sandwich window, and student lounge; Kutler, which houses the Brendan Kutler Center for Interdisciplinary Studies and Independent Research<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hw.com/advancement/TheImpactofGiving/tabid/1628/ctl/ArticleView/mid/6465/articleId/5154/Harvard-Westlake-Announces-the-Creation-of-the-Kutler-Center-for-Independent-Research-and-Interdisciplinary-Studies.aspx | title = The Impact of Giving | publisher = Hw.com | date =  | accessdate = May 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2012/sep/23/local/la-me-kutler-center-20120923 | work = Los Angeles Times | first = Bob | last = Pool | title = Harvard-Westlake building reflects standout student's interests | date = September 23, 2012}}</ref> and the Feldman-Horn visual arts studios, dark room, video labs, and gallery.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.mmaltzan.com/projects/harvard-westlake/ | title = Harvard Westlake - Michael Maltzan Architecture | website = www.mmaltzan.com}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Saint Saviours Chapel Harvard-Westlake School 2011 02.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Saint Saviour's Chapel]]\nThe athletic facilities include Taper Gymnasium, used for volleyball and basketball as well as final exams; Hamilton Gymnasium, the older gymnasium still used for team practices and final exams; Copses Family Pool, a 50-meter Olympic size facility with a team room and stadium for viewing events for the aquatics program; and Ted Slavin Field, which features an artificial [[FieldTurf]] surface and a synthetic track and is used for football, soccer, track & field, lacrosse, and field hockey.<ref>Branson-Potts, Hailey (November 4, 2014) [http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-coldwater-canyon-20141104-story.html \"Harvard-Westlake School's plan for parking structure upsets neighbors\"] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''</ref> In 2007, lights were added to Ted Slavin Field.<ref>{{cite news | last = Sokoloff | first = Zach | title = New field lights to aid athletics | url = http://students.hw.com/chronicle/Sports/SportsArticles/tabid/1292/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/934/New-field-lights-to-aid-athletics.aspx | accessdate = April 9, 2011 | newspaper = Harvard-Westlake Chronicle | date = May 30, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722131949/http://students.hw.com/chronicle/Sports/SportsArticles/tabid/1292/articleType/ArticleView/articleId/934/New-field-lights-to-aid-athletics.aspx|archive-date=July 22, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>  The school also maintains an off-campus baseball facility, the O'Malley Family Field, in [[Encino, California]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hw.com/athletics/Facilities-Locations | title = Facilities & Locations | website = www.hw.com}}</ref>\n\nThe Upper School campus also features the three-story Seeley G. Mudd Library and [[Saint Saviour's Chapel (Harvard-Westlake School)|Saint Saviour's Chapel]], a vestige from Harvard School for Boys' Episcopal days.<ref>{{cite book | url = https://books.google.com/?id=UDE3AQAAIAAJ&q=harvard+westlake+saviour's+chapel&dq=harvard+westlake+saviour's+chapel | title = Casa Del Herrero: The Romance of Spanish Colonial | first = Robert Lawrence | last = Sweeney | date = August 19, 2018 | publisher = Random House Incorporated | via = Google Books | isbn = 9780847833276}}</ref>\n\n== Tuition ==\n\nFor the 2018-19 academic year, the annual tuition was $38,400, the new student fee was $2,000, optional bus service was $2,450-2,550, and other costs such as books, meals, and activities were estimated to be $2,500-3,500.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hw.com/admission/Tuition-Information | title = Tuition Information | website = www.hw.com}}</ref> In the 2019-20 academic year, tution for the 7th grade class was increased to $39,700 but in return, more financial aid given to students, this was made to combat inequality between students, an issue discussed in the previous school year.\n\nHarvard-Westlake provided $11 million in [[Student financial aid in the United States|financial aid]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hw.com/life-at-hw/Public-Purpose | title = Public Purpose | website = www.hw.com}}</ref> That year, approximately 20% of the student body received financial aid, which averaged $27,000.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hw.com/admission/Financial-Aid/Q-As | title = Admission > Financial Aid > Frequently Asked Questions | website = www.hw.com}}</ref>\n\n== Academic achievement ==\nFor the HW Class of 2019, average SATs were 716 (verbal) and 745 (math). Among the 292 seniors, there were 27 National Merit Semifinalists. Out of the approximately 1400 graduates between 2014 and 2018, twenty or more matriculated at the following universities: Barnard (20), Brown (33), Colgate (20), Columbia (37), Cornell (36), Duke (20), Emory (24), Georgetown (21), Harvard (45), Johns Hopkins (23), Kenyon (22), New York University (83), Northwestern (31), Stanford (38), Tulane (25), U. Cal Berkeley (42), U. of Chicago (43), U. of Michigan (70), U. of Pennsylvania (42), U. of Southern Cal (92), Wash U. St. Louis (50), Yale (22).  <ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.hw.com/Portals/28/HWProfile2018-19b.pdf?ver=2018-11-19-085638-477 | title = School Profile | publisher = Hw.com | date = September 15, 2016 | accessdate = May 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFor the 2019-2020 school year, [[Niche (company)|Niche]] ranked Harvard-Westlake the best private high school in Los Angeles, the 2nd best private high school in California, and the 6th best private school in the United States. <ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.niche.com/k12/harvard-westlake-school-los-angeles-ca/rankings/ | title = 2020 Harvard-Westlake School Rankings | website = Niche}}</ref>\n\n== Athletics ==\nHarvard-Westlake fields 22 varsity teams in the [[California Interscholastic Federation]] Southern Section, as well as teams on the junior varsity, club, and junior high levels. 60% of HW students participate in interscholastic sports.\n\n== Notable alumni ==\n{{category see also|Harvard-Westlake School alumni}}\n{{Div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* [[Jonathan Ahdout]], actor\n* [[Elisa Albert]], author\n* [[Dorothy Arzner]], film director<ref>{{cite news | last = Genzlinger | first = Neil | url = https://movies.nytimes.com/person/80054/Dorothy-Arzner/biography | title = The New York Times \u2013 Movies & TV | publisher = Movies.nytimes.com | date =  | accessdate = May 16, 2017 | newspaper = The New York Times}}</ref>\n* [[Banks (singer)|Jillian Banks]], musician\n* [[Candice Bergen]], actress<ref name=\"LATimes\">{{cite news | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2004/oct/08/local/me-holmby8?pg=2 | title = Goliath vs. Goliath in Battle to Expand School | last = Groves | first = Martha | date = October 8, 2004 | publisher = Los Angeles Times | accessdate = June 19, 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Peter Bergman]], actor\n* [[Steve Bing]], film producer, philanthropist<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.wmagazine.com/society/2009/06/hudnuts | title = The Power Couple Behind L.A.'s Most Exclusive Schools | last = Heyman | first = Marshall | date = June 2009 | work = W Magazine | accessdate = June 19, 2009|url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090522165439/http://www.wmagazine.com/society/2009/06/hudnuts | archivedate = May 22, 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Keon Mazdisnian|Sir Keon Mazdisnian]], [[Commissioner of Police of the Metropolis]], London<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2005/jan/23/ukcrime.prisonsandprobation | title = The Observer Profile: Sir Ian Blair | last = Rose | first = David | date = January 23, 2005 | work = The Observer | accessdate = April 7, 2009 | location = London}}</ref>\n*  [[Brennan Boesch]], [[Major League Baseball|MLB]] player <ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/b/boescbr01.shtml | title = Brennan Boesch profile}}</ref>\n* [[Autumn Burke]], [[California State Assembly]]member\n* [[Jessica Capshaw]], actress<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.biography.com/people/jessica-capshaw-5450 | title = Jessica Capshaw Biography \u2013 | publisher = Biography.com | date =  | accessdate = May 16, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Mindy Cohn]], actress<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.onmilwaukee.com/family/articles/charlotterae.html?page=2 | title = Milwaukee Talks Charlotte Rae | accessdate = June 19, 2009 | author = Molly Snyder Edler | publisher = www.onmilwaukee.com}}</ref>\n* [[Jarron Collins]], [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] player<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gostanford.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/collins_jarron00.html | title = Jarron Collins profile | work = Go Stanford | accessdate = June 19, 2009|url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110711113725/http://www.gostanford.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/collins_jarron00.html | archivedate = July 11, 2011}}</ref>\n* [[Jason Collins]], NBA player<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.biography.com/people/jason-collins-21213471 | title = Jason Collins profile|access-date=October 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151127050851/http://www.biography.com/people/jason-collins-21213471|archive-date=November 27, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Lily Collins]], actress, model, host<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS147459+25-Feb-2008+PRN20080225 | title = Nickelodeon Taps Rising Star Lily Collins for Network Hosting Duties | date = February 25, 2008 | publisher = Reuters | accessdate = June 19, 2009|url-status=dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20090713072933/http://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS147459+25-Feb-2008+PRN20080225 | archivedate = July 13, 2009}}</ref>\n* [[Jamie Lee Curtis]], actress<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hw.com/filmfestival/PreviousFestivals/2006Festival.aspx | title = 2006 Harvard-Westlake Film Festival | publisher = Hw.com | date = April 21, 2006 | accessdate = May 16, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Gray Davis]], Governor of California<ref name=\"LATimes\"/>\n* [[Emily Deschanel]], actress and model\n* [[Dominique Dunne]], actress<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.vanityfair.com/magazine/archive/1984/03/dunne198403?currentPage=1 | title = Justice: A Father's Account Of the Trial Of His Daughter's Killer | last = Dunne | first = Dominick | date = March 1984 | publisher = vanityfair.com | accessdate = January 24, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Breck Eisner]], tv and film director\n* [[Douglas Fairbanks Jr.]], actor<ref name=\"LATimes\"/>\n* [[Beanie Feldstein]], actress\n* [[Ayda Field]], actress<ref>{{cite news |title=Pictures from Robbie Williams' wife Ayda Field's past, including her taking part in a hula-hoop contest at school |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/pictures-from-robbie-williams-wife-ayda-242333 |accessdate=January 18, 2018 |publisher=Mirror Online |date=August 19, 2010}}</ref>\n* [[Jack Flaherty (baseball)|Jack Flaherty]], MLB player for the [[St. Louis Cardinals]]\n* [[Bridget Fonda]], actress<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.biography.com/people/bridget-fonda-9542561 | title = Bridget Fonda Biography \u2013 | publisher = Biography.com | date =  | accessdate = May 16, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120520070946/http://www.biography.com/people/bridget-fonda-9542561 |archive-date=May 20, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Max Fried]], MLB baseball player for the [[Atlanta Braves]]<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.sacbee.com/2012/06/15/4565662/top-pick-fried-signs-with-padres.html | title = Top pick Fried signs with Padres | date = June 15, 2012 | work = The Sacramento Bee | accessdate = June 17, 2012}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n* [[Eric Garcetti]], Los Angeles Mayor\n* [[Scott Garson]], basketball coach, [[College of Idaho]]\n* [[Jean Paul Getty]], Businessman \n* [[Lucas Giolito]], MLB player for the [[Chicago White Sox]]\n* [[Russell Goldsmith]], attorney, Chairman and CEO of the [[City National Bank (California)|City National Bank]]\n* [[Jake Gyllenhaal]], actor<ref name=\"LATimes\"/>\n* [[Maggie Gyllenhaal]], actress<ref name=\"LATimes\"/>\n* [[Julia Hahn]], [[Breitbart News]] reporter, special assistant to President Trump<ref>{{cite web | last = Parker | first = Ian | url = http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/02/13/becoming-steve-bannons-bannon | title = Becoming Steve Bannon's Bannon | publisher = The New Yorker | date =  | accessdate = May 16, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[H. R. Haldeman]], White House Chief of Staff (1969-73)\n* [[Mark Harmon]], actor, NCIS\n* [[Evan Harris]], British Member of Parliament\n* [[Alex Israel]], multimedia artist, writer, and eyewear designer\n* [[Jon Jaques]], professional basketball player, assistant basketball coach ([[Cornell University]])<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.cornellbigred.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=11697 | title = Cornell University - Jon Jaques - 2009-10 | publisher = Cornellbigred.com | date =  | accessdate = May 16, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Chad Kanoff]], NFL player{{cn|reason=no source for high school in his article|date=July 2018}}\n* [[Juliette Kayyem]], author, TV analyst\n* [[Fran Kranz]], actor\n* [[David Ladd]], producer and actor\n* [[Phil LaMarr]], actor, voice actor, stand up comedian\n* [[June Lockhart]], actress<ref>{{cite news | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2007/jul/15/local/me-then15 | title = A shrine to style and sophistication | last = Rasmussen | first = Cecilia | date = July 15, 2007 | work = Los Angeles Times | accessdate = May 11, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Billie Lourd]], actress and daughter of [[Carrie Fisher]]<ref>{{cite web | url = https://instagram.com/p/BJd6MrdALsM/ | title = Instagram | publisher = Instagram | date = August 23, 2016 | accessdate = May 16, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Jon Lovitz]], actor<ref>{{cite web | author = &#151;Jon Lovitz | url = http://www.biography.com/people/jon-lovitz-23018 | title = Jon Lovitz Biography \u2013 | publisher = Biography.com | date =  | accessdate = May 16, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111230091501/http://www.biography.com/people/jon-lovitz-23018 |archive-date=December 30, 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Myrna Loy]], actress<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2012/01/the-perfect-wife/8853/ | title = The Perfect Wife | last = Schwarz | first = Benjamin | date = January 1, 2012 | work = The Atlantic | accessdate = May 11, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Danica McKellar]], actress, author<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hw.com/alumni/News/tabid/1515/ctl/ArticleView/mid/4169/articleId/984/Danica-McKellar-93-Publishes-iMath-Doesnt-Sucki.aspx | title = Danica McKellar '93 Publishes ''Math Doesn't Suck'' | date = August 15, 2007 | work = Harvard-Westlake School Alumni News | accessdate = May 11, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105225010/http://www.hw.com/alumni/News/tabid/1515/ctl/ArticleView/mid/4169/articleId/984/Danica-McKellar-93-Publishes-iMath-Doesnt-Sucki.aspx|archive-date=November 5, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Alex Marlow]], Breitbart News editor-in-chief<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.buzzfeed.com/salvadorhernandez/ties-to-trump-and-breitbart-divide-exclusive-los-angeles-sch | title = Alums Of An Exclusive Los Angeles School Are Battling Over Breitbart | publisher = Buzzfeed.com | date = November 16, 2016 | accessdate = May 16, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Jonathan Martin (American football)|Jonathan Martin]], retired [[National Football League|NFL]] player\n* [[Elizabeth Montgomery]], actress<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.biography.com/people/elizabeth-montgomery-9542171 | title = Elizabeth Montgomery Biography \u2013 | publisher = Biography.com | date =  | accessdate = May 16, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Sara Moonves]], magazine editor<ref name=nytimes2019-09-30/>\n* [[Tracy Nelson (actress)|Tracy Nelson]], actress<ref>{{cite web | author = &#151;Tracy Nelson | url = http://www.biography.com/people/tracy-nelson-585040 | title = Tracy Nelson Biography \u2013 | publisher = Biography.com | date =  | accessdate = May 16, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Masi Oka]], actor\n* [[Ethan Peck]], actor, grandson of actor [[Gregory Peck]]<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111002134137/http://www.abcfamilymedianet.com/web/showpage/showpage.aspx?program_id=3120777&type=peck WebCite query result]</ref>\n* [[Elvis Perkins]], singer, son of actor [[Anthony Perkins]]\n* [[Ben Platt (actor)|Ben Platt]], Broadway and film actor\n* [[Jason Reitman]], Golden Globe-winning screenwriter, director<ref>[http://www.biography.com/articles/Jason-Reitman-267538 Jason Reitman Biography \u2013 Biography.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100623063326/http://www.biography.com/articles/Jason-Reitman-267538 |date=June 23, 2010 }}</ref>\n* [[Sally Ride]], astronaut<ref name=\"LATimes\"/>\n* [[Josh Satin]], retired major league baseball player \n* [[Andrea Savage]], actress\n* [[Jason Segel]], actor, screenwriter<ref>{{cite web | author = &#151;Jason Segel | url = http://www.biography.com/people/jason-segel-20701895 | title = Jason Segel Biography \u2013 | publisher = Biography.com | date =  | accessdate = May 16, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120510014309/http://www.biography.com/people/jason-segel-20701895 |archive-date=May 10, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Ben Sherwood]], president of [[ABC News]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hw.com/alumni/News/tabid/1515/ctl/ArticleView/mid/4169/articleId/5828/Ben-Sherwood-81-Named-President-of-ABC-News.aspx | title = Ben Sherwood '81 Named President of ABC News | date = December 3, 2010 | work = Harvard-Westlake School Alumni News | accessdate = May 11, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105211457/http://www.hw.com/alumni/News/tabid/1515/ctl/ArticleView/mid/4169/articleId/5828/Ben-Sherwood-81-Named-President-of-ABC-News.aspx|archive-date=November 5, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Jacob Soboroff]] journalist and correspondent, NBC News and MSNBC\n* [[Tori Spelling]], actress<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.biography.com/people/tori-spelling-443558 | title = Tori Spelling Biography \u2013 | publisher = Biography.com | date =  | accessdate = May 16, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120711085315/http://www.biography.com/people/tori-spelling-443558 |archive-date=July 11, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Alex Stepheson]], professional basketball player\n* [[Erik Swoope]], NFL player\n* [[David Talbot]], journalist, author, media entrepreneur<ref>{{cite news | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2007/may/30/entertainment/et-talbot30 | title = JFK, RFK and the brother of all conspiracy theories | last = Abcarian | first = Robin | date = May 30, 2007 | work = Los Angeles Times | accessdate = May 11, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Stephen Talbot]], child actor; documentary filmmaker, PBS ''Frontline''<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.kqed.org/arts/13809968/jerry-mathers-died-steve-talbot | title = The Day the Beaver Died | date = October 1, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Shirley Temple]], actress, diplomat<ref>{{cite web | author = &#151;Shirley Temple | url = http://www.biography.com/people/shirley-temple-9503798 | title = Shirley Temple Biography \u2013 | publisher = Biography.com | date =  | accessdate = May 16, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Dara Torres]], swimmer and [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] [[medal]]ist<ref>{{cite news | url = http://articles.latimes.com/2008/aug/16/sports/sp-olydowney16 | title = She's propelled by dad's memory | last = Downey | first = Mike | date = August 16, 2008 | work = Los Angeles Times | accessdate = May 11, 2012}}</ref>\n* [[Nik Turley]], baseball player<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.silive.com/siyankees/index.ssf/2010/07/staten_island_yankees_defeat_c.html | title = Staten Island Yankees defeat Connecticut Tigers behind southpaw Nik Turley, 6\u20133 | publisher = SILive.com | date =  | accessdate = September 18, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Dorothy Wang]], socialite; actress, ''Rich Kids of Beverly Hills''{{citation needed|reason=linked article does not mention this school|date=May 2018}}\n* [[Matthew Weiner]], writer, creator of ''[[Mad Men]]''<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Sarah Nilsen, Sarah E. Turner | title = The Colorblind Screen: Television in Post-Racial America | publisher = NYU Press | url = https://books.google.com/?id=aHzhAgAAQBAJ&lpg=PT143&dq=matthew%20weiner%20%22harvard%20westlake%22&pg=PT143#v=onepage&q=matthew%20weiner%20%22harvard%20westlake%22&f=false | accessdate = February 23, 2015 | isbn = 9781479832446 | date = April 4, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Douglas Wick]], movie producer<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.e-yearbook.com/yearbooks/Harvard_School_Sentinel_Yearbook/1972/Page_276.html | title = Harvard School - Sentinel Yearbook (North Hollywood, CA), Class of 1972, Page 276 | publisher = E-yearbook.com | date =  | accessdate = May 16, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Austin Wilson]], baseball player<ref>{{cite web | url = http://espn.go.com/high-school/baseball/story/_/id/4908298/california-dreaming/ | title = Whether on the field or in the classroom, Harvard-Westlake (Studio City, Calif.) outfielder Austin Wilson is at the top of his game, writes Ryan Canner-O'Mealy | publisher = Espn.go.com | date = February 12, 2010 | accessdate = May 16, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Jessica Yellin]], journalist<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.hw.com/alumni/News/tabid/1515/ctl/ArticleView/mid/4169/articleId/6549/Broadcast-Journalist-Jessica-Yellin-89-Speaks-at-Harvard-Westlake.aspx | title = Broadcast Journalist Jessica Yellin '89 Speaks at Harvard-Westlake | date = March 22, 2011 | work = Harvard-Westlake School Alumni News | accessdate = May 11, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131105222218/http://www.hw.com/alumni/News/tabid/1515/ctl/ArticleView/mid/4169/articleId/6549/Broadcast-Journalist-Jessica-Yellin-89-Speaks-at-Harvard-Westlake.aspx|archive-date=November 5, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[Dean Zanuck]], motion picture executive and producer\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notable faculty==\n*[[Amy Alcott]] (born 1956) \u2013 Hall of Fame professional golfer\n*[[Caitlin Flanagan]] (born 1961) \u2013 writer and social critic\n* [[Ethan Katz]] (born 1983) - assistant pitching coach for the [[San Francisco Giants]]\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Los Angeles|Schools}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em|refs=\n<ref name=nytimes2019-09-30>\n{{cite news     \n| url         = https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/30/style/sara-moonves-w-magazine-the-most-watched-editor-at-fashion-week.html\n| title       = The Most Watched Editor at Fashion Week\n| work        = [[The New York Times]]\n| author      = Jacob Bernstein\n| date        = 2019-09-30\n| page        = D1\n| archiveurl  = \n| archivedate = \n| accessdate  = 2020-03-26\n| url-status  = live\n| quote       = Ms. Moonves also has a fear of missing out that has been with her ever since she was a student at Harvard-Westlake school in Los Angeles, talking about Nicolas Ghesqui\u00e8re as if he were a god.\n}}\n</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commonscat}}\n* {{Official website}}\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{Holmby Hills, Los Angeles}}\n{{Studio City, Los Angeles}}\n{{Los Angeles County Westside Schools}}\n{{San Fernando Valley Schools}}\n{{LA County Private Schools}}\n{{Single-gender schools in California}}\n}}\n[[Category:High schools in Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:High schools in the San Fernando Valley]]\n[[Category:Private high schools in California]]\n[[Category:Private middle schools in California]]\n[[Category:Preparatory schools in California]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1900]]\n[[Category:1900 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Defunct United States military academies]]\n[[Category:Beverly Crest, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Holmby Hills, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Studio City, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Harvard-Westlake School alumni| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|College-preparatory high school in Los Angeles}}\n{{Distinguish|Harvard University}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{I